text: Though we've not spoken for many years, Jesse used to be a good friend of mine in secondary school. Back then we knew him as 'the Dealer', as a crippling bout of diarhorrea in the summer of 2005 rendered him lactose intolerant for the majority of his adolescence. This culminated in him still collecting his daily carton of milk from the canteen but, for a price, you could 'buy a sip' from him to increase your own dairy ration. Most lunchtimes I'd follow him to the bike sheds  (he called them the milking parlour) where he'd reveal the inside pocket of his blazer, bulging with its concealed creamy goodness. After casting a quick look around to ensure the coast was clear I'd lean into his blazer, pressing my head close to his chest and begin sucking on the plastic straw to get my moneys worth. Once I'd had my fill I'd stand back up, give him a firm handshake (through which the 20p was exchanged) and we'd get on with our respective days. I miss him dearly.
